<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-147-356  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 147 356.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Transactions on Computers  April 1989 v38 n4 p555(12).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A group-theoretic model for symmetric interconnection networks.andO;(technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Akers, Sheldon B.; Krishnamurthy, Balakrishnan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Processor-communication interconnection networks often take theform of symmetric graphs.andP;  Network performance can be measuredthrough analysis of such factors as degree, connectivity,diameter, routing algorithms or fault tolerance.andP;  A formalgroup-theoretic Cayley graph model is developed for the design,analysis and improvement of such networks.andP;  The model is shown tobe universal and capable of concise representation of suchnetworks.andP;  It is also shown that the model can be employed todesign new networks based on representations of finite groups,with those networks subject to analysis by theoreticalinterpretation of the group-theoretic structure graph.andP;  Finally,two new classes of networks which offer superior performance, stargraphs and pancake graphs, are developed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     GraphsNetworksAlgorithmsModelsModeling of Computer SystemsFault Tolerance.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphtable.andO;Caption:   Cayley graphs. (graph)Star graph. (graph)A comparison of an n-cube and an n-star graph. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>